Q46:
1.	What will happen to me in this research study? 
In this study you will first answer a few questions about creativity.
You will then complete a small 2-minute task asking you to come up with as many uses as you can for an object.
You will repeat this same task 4 more times, and you might be able to use a tool to help you.
Afterwards you will complete another 4-minute task asking you to come up with diverse words, and again, you might be able to use a tool to help you.
You will finally answer more questions about creativity.

2.	How long will I be in this research study?
 Participation in this study will take a total of about 20 minutes.

3.	Can anything bad happen to me? 
While we do not anticipate anything bad happening to you, there is a very small possibility that your responses for this study could be leaked to other people. Completing all of the tasks could also be difficult and could require a lot of concentration and thinking.

If you become sick or in pain as a result of participating in this study, please let your teacher or your parent know immediately. Tell your parent to reach out to the research team about this.

4.	Can anything good happen to me?
As a result of participating in this study, you could potentially become more creative and better at thinking of different ways to use objects. We hope that your work can help more children learn how to become more creative. 

5.	Will anyone know I am in the study?
No one will know that you are in this study, but your responses will be used by the research team to better understand how children use tools for creativity.

6.	Will I receive any Payment if I participate in this study? 
You will not receive anything for being in the study.

7.	What if I do not want to do this? 
At any point in time, you may stop being in the study. You will not be in any trouble at all for deciding to stop or to not finish.

8.	Who can I talk to about the study?
If you have any questions about the study or any problems to do with the study you can contact the Protocol Director, Sachin Allums. You can call them at 512-698-2190 or email them at sachino@stanford.edu. You can also email Dr. Ari Kelman at aykelman@stanford.edu.

If you have questions about the study but want to talk to someone else who is not a part of the study, you can call the Stanford Institutional Review Board (IRB) at 650-723-2480 or toll free at 1-866-680-2906.
